<subSubSection id="02C66578FFF7FFB6FF3D9A876B517ADF" pageId="26" pageNumber="40" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFF7FFB6FF3D9A87683B7B9A" blockId="26.[151,756,1731,1982]" pageId="26" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFF7FFB6FF3D9A8768057BBA" bold="true" box="[151,264,1731,1755]" pageId="26" pageNumber="40">Remarks:</emphasis>
It resembles the specimens recorded by LUGER (1985).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFF7FFB6FF3D9B406B517ADF" blockId="26.[151,756,1731,1982]" pageId="26" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFF7FFB6FF3D9B4068C47A7D" bold="true" box="[151,457,1796,1820]" pageId="26" pageNumber="40">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
It was originally described from the American Late Cretaceous. Also, it is recorded from the basal Eocene of Maqfi Section, 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFF7FFB6FDE09B016B877A3C" box="[586,650,1861,1885]" name="Egypt" pageId="26" pageNumber="40">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(LE ROY, 1953) but SAID &amp; KENAWY (1956) recorded a longer range than LE ROY believed. In the study area, it is found in the Maastrichtian and Paleocene Zones.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
